---
export const prerender = true;
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
import BlogCrossLinks from '../../components/BlogCrossLinks.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
---

<BlogLayout
  title="Preparing for Your First Scrabble Tournament — Complete Guide"
  description="Everything you need before your first rated Scrabble event. What to study, what to bring, clock management, mental prep, and how to handle nerves. Free tips from experienced tournament players."
  keywords="first scrabble tournament, scrabble tournament preparation, scrabble tournament tips, competitive scrabble beginner, scrabble tournament what to bring, tournament clock scrabble"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Preparing for Your First Scrabble Tournament",
    "description": "Everything you need before your first rated Scrabble event. What to study, what to bring, clock management, mental prep, and how to handle nerves.",
    "datePublished": "2026-06-15",
    "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "logo": { "@type": "ImageObject", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/web-app-manifest-512x512.png" } },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/preparing-for-first-tournament/" }
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do I prepare for my first Scrabble tournament?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Memorise all 2-letter words, learn common 3-letter words, practice with a tournament clock (25 minutes per player), study basic strategy (rack management, bingo hunting), and play rated games online to gauge your level. Most importantly, expect to lose early and learn from every game." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What should I bring to a Scrabble tournament?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Bring: a pen for scorekeeping, water and snacks, your own timer (as backup), comfortable clothing, entry fees, and a positive attitude. The venue provides boards, tiles, and official word lists. Some players bring tile bags and a tile tracking sheet." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How are Scrabble tournaments structured?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Most tournaments use Swiss-system pairing where you play opponents with similar records. Expect 5-7 games per day over 1-3 days. Games use 25-minute chess clocks per player. Divisions separate beginners from experts. Prizes go to top finishers in each division." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How many words should I memorise before my first tournament?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "At minimum, know all 127 two-letter words and the most common three-letter words (around 200). Learn the Q-without-U words (QI, QOPH, QADI, etc.), high-value J/X/Z words, and a handful of 7-letter bingo stems. This gives you a solid foundation without overwhelming memorisation." }
      }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-amber-500 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Tournament & Competitive</span>
      </nav>

      <BlogCrossLinks title="Preparing for Your First Scrabble Tournament" />

      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-15">June 15, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-300 dark:bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>10 min read</span>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-8">
        Your first rated Scrabble tournament is equal parts exciting and terrifying. The good news: preparation eliminates most of the anxiety. This guide covers exactly what to study, what to pack, how to manage the clock, and how to keep your nerves from sabotaging your word knowledge. By the time you walk into that venue, you will feel ready.
      </p>

      <!-- Hero Card -->
      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">🎯 First Tournament</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">FROM LIVING ROOM TO TOURNAMENT HALL</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">25-min clocks · Swiss pairing · Rated games · Division play</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">Most first-time tournament players overthink the preparation. The truth is simpler: know your two-letter words, manage your clock, bring water, and accept that losing is learning. Everything else is a bonus.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Stat Strip -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">25 min</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Per player on the clock</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">5–7</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Games per tournament day</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">127</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Two-letter words to know</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">50 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Bingo bonus for using all 7 tiles</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 1: What to Study -->
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">What to Study Before Your First Tournament</h2>

      <p>You do not need to know the entire dictionary. Focus on the highest-impact words that separate tournament players from kitchen-table players. The difference between finishing mid-pack and finishing last is usually two-letter word knowledge and basic rack management.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">🧩 Study Priority Order (4 Weeks Before)</p>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">1</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">All 127 Two-Letter Words</strong> — non-negotiable. These enable parallel plays, score in tight spots, and are the single biggest knowledge gap for newcomers. Spend week one on nothing else.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">2</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Q-Without-U Words</strong> — QI, QOPH, QADI, QAID, QANAT. If you draw the Q without a U, you need an escape plan. These words are your safety net.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">3</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">High-Value Short Words</strong> — ZA, ZO, XI, XU, JO, AX, EX, OX. Three-letter words with J, X, Z that consistently score 25-40 on premium squares.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">4</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Common 7-Letter Bingo Stems</strong> — SATIRE, RETAIN, NASTIER. Even spotting one bingo in a tournament game gives you a 50-point bonus that can swing the result.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">5</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Basic Hook Words</strong> — letters that extend existing words on the board (adding S, D, R, or rare hooks). Hooks let you score on two words simultaneously.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 The 80/20 Rule</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Knowing all <span class="text-white font-medium">127 two-letter words</span> and the <span class="text-white font-medium">top 50 three-letter power words</span> covers roughly 80% of the scoring opportunities you will encounter in your first tournament. Perfect is the enemy of ready — go with solid fundamentals over incomplete advanced knowledge.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Inline Cross-Links -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">📚 Dig Deeper</p>
        <div class="grid gap-2">
          <a href="/blog/two-letter-words/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">Two-Letter Words Hub — complete list with memorisation tips</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/first-10-words-to-learn-scrabble/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">First 10 Words to Learn — essential vocabulary for new competitive players</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 2: What to Bring -->
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">What to Bring on Tournament Day</h2>

      <p>Venues provide the boards, tiles, and official word reference. But experienced players always bring extras that make the day more comfortable and reduce stress. Think of it like exam day — preparation removes uncertainty.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Essential Items</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Pen (for scorekeeping), water bottle, snacks (energy bars, fruit), entry fee (cash or pre-paid), comfortable clothing, and a watch or phone for break timing.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Recommended Extras</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Backup timer (in case venue timer breaks), tile tracking sheet, earplugs (for concentration during noisy rounds), spare pen, and a small notebook for post-game notes.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10">
          <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✗ Do NOT Bring</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Electronic word lists or dictionaries (banned during play), your own tiles (use venue equipment), or any attitude that expects to win every game on your first outing.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">⚡ Pro Tip</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Eat a proper breakfast. Tournament days run 6-8 hours. Low blood sugar in game 5 destroys concentration faster than any word gap. Pack protein-heavy snacks, not sugar.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 3: Clock Management -->
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Clock Management for First-Timers</h2>

      <p>The chess clock is the single biggest shock for players coming from casual games. You have 25 minutes total for all your moves. Running out means 10 points deducted per minute over — and an automatic loss if you exceed by too much. Here is how to manage your time intelligently.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">25 min</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Your total clock time</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">12–15</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Typical turns per game</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">~90 sec</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Average time per turn</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">-10 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Penalty per overtime minute</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Opening moves (turns 1-3):</span> Play quickly. The board is open, options are limited, and overthinking costs precious minutes. Aim for under 60 seconds per turn in the early game.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Mid-game (turns 4-10):</span> This is where you should spend time. The board is complex, scoring opportunities are nuanced, and a well-placed word here decides the game. Budget 2-3 minutes for critical turns.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Endgame (turns 11+):</span> Speed up again. With fewer tiles left, the options narrow. If you have been disciplined, you should have 5-7 minutes banked for any tricky endgame decisions.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">The 5-minute warning rule:</span> When you hit 5 minutes remaining, accept the best move you can see within 30 seconds. A slightly suboptimal play is always better than a time penalty. Never burn clock hunting for a bingo you cannot find.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-cyan-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">🔬 Practice Before the Event</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Play at least <span class="text-white font-medium">10 timed games</span> online before your first tournament. Use a phone timer if needed. The goal is not to play fast — it is to develop a <span class="text-white font-medium">sense of pace</span>. After 10 games, you will intuitively know when you are spending too long on a turn without checking the clock.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 4: Tournament Structure -->
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">How Tournament Day Actually Works</h2>

      <p>Walking into a venue full of experienced players can feel intimidating. Knowing the structure in advance removes the uncertainty. Here is what a typical one-day tournament looks like from registration to final standings.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">🧩 Typical Tournament Day Flow</p>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">1</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Registration (30-60 min before)</strong> — check in, pay entry fee, receive your player number. Pair boards are posted showing your first opponent.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">2</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Round 1 Announcement</strong> — the director calls players to their assigned tables. Shake hands, draw tiles to determine who goes first (closest to A plays first).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">3</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Game Play (45-60 min per game)</strong> — both players have 25 minutes on their clock. Challenges are resolved by the word judge (or electronic adjudicator). Record final scores on the result slip.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">4</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Swiss Pairing Between Rounds</strong> — after each round, the director pairs you with someone who has a similar win/loss record. This means games get progressively more evenly matched.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">5</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Breaks (15-30 min)</strong> — usually a lunch break after game 3 or 4. Use this to reset mentally, hydrate, and review your earlier games.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">6</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Final Standings + Prizes</strong> — after all rounds, standings are posted. Winners receive prizes per division. Spread (point difference) is the tiebreaker.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 5: Mental Prep & Handling Nerves -->
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Mental Preparation and Handling Nerves</h2>

      <p>Nearly every first-time tournament player reports the same experience: their word knowledge seems to evaporate under pressure. Words they know perfectly in practice refuse to surface when the clock is ticking. This is normal — and manageable with the right mental framework.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Set Process Goals</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Instead of "I want to win 4 games," aim for "I will check all my two-letter options every turn" or "I will track time after every 3 turns." Process goals keep you focused on what you can control.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Expect to Lose Early</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Most first-timers lose their opening games. This is fine. Swiss pairing means you will face opponents at your level by games 3-4. Your real tournament starts in the middle rounds.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Breathe Between Turns</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">When your opponent plays, take one slow breath. This micro-reset prevents adrenaline from building. Chronic tension narrows vision — you miss plays that a calm mind would spot instantly.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Forget the Last Game</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">A devastating loss in game 2 cannot affect game 3 — unless you carry it mentally. Between rounds, walk outside, drink water, and reset. Each game starts at 0-0 regardless of your day so far.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 The Biggest First-Timer Mistake</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Playing <span class="text-white font-medium">not to lose</span> instead of playing <span class="text-white font-medium">to learn</span>. Defensive, timid play out of fear leads to worse results than confident play with occasional mistakes. Every game at your first tournament is a learning opportunity — embrace it, make bold plays, and review afterwards with a word finder to see what you missed.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 6: Tournament Etiquette -->
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Tournament Etiquette — What Every Newcomer Should Know</h2>

      <p>Tournament Scrabble has unwritten rules that experienced players follow instinctively. Knowing these in advance prevents awkward moments and helps you fit in from game one.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Shake hands before and after:</span> Always. Win or lose. It is the universal signal of sportsmanship in competitive Scrabble and establishes mutual respect.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Keep quiet during play:</span> No comments on your rack, no sighing about bad tiles, no reactions to your opponent's words. Silence is expected. Save discussion for after the game.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Challenge respectfully:</span> If you think a word is not valid, say "Challenge" calmly. The word judge decides. Never argue the ruling. A wrong challenge (the word IS valid) costs you your turn — so challenge only when fairly sure.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Announce your score clearly:</span> After placing tiles, state your score aloud so your opponent can verify. Both players track the running total on their score sheets. Discrepancies are resolved immediately.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Do not slam the clock:</span> Press your clock button firmly but gently. Aggressive clock-hitting is considered bad form and can intimidate newer players. Be mindful of shared space.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Inline Cross-Links -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">🔗 Related Guides</p>
        <div class="grid gap-2">
          <a href="/blog/how-scrabble-tournaments-work/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">How Scrabble Tournaments Work — deep dive into formats and scoring</span>
