              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Comfortable with pace, relaxed under pressure</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">✅ Ready Check</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">You are ready for your first tournament when you can: <span class="text-white font-medium">recite all two-letter words on demand</span>, <span class="text-white font-medium">complete a game in under 25 minutes comfortably</span>, and <span class="text-white font-medium">play without emotional reaction to bad tiles</span>. You do NOT need to know every word in the dictionary. You just need solid fundamentals and composure.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 8: After the Tournament -->
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">After Your First Tournament — What Comes Next</h2>

      <p>The day after your first tournament is when the real growth happens. You will have stories, missed words, and lessons that no amount of home practice could teach. Here is how to extract maximum value from the experience.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Review every game:</span> Write down the words you did not know, the plays you missed, and the clock decisions that cost you. Use a word finder to check what the best move was on your trickiest racks.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Build your missed-words list:</span> Every word an opponent played that you did not know goes on a study list. These are the words at YOUR skill boundary — the fastest path to improving your rating.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Connect with players:</span> Exchange contacts with 2-3 players at a similar level. Regular practice partners accelerate improvement more than solo study. Most tournament communities are welcoming to newcomers.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Register for the next one:</span> The second tournament is where you actually compete. The first one was about learning the environment. Most players see their biggest rating jumps between tournaments 2 and 5.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

